1. Definitions are tools, not laws

In good systems design:

A definition is not reality.
A definition is a compression of current understanding.

When reality improves or new constraints appear, the definition should evolve.

This is why:
	•	scientific theories update
	•	military doctrine revisions exist
	•	software uses version numbers
	•	constitutions have amendments

A rigid definition eventually becomes technical debt.

A versioned definition becomes knowledge infrastructure.

